column1: Desperate Fishing Crews Fight Against Winter with Dwindling Supplies | Deadliest Catch | Discovery
column5:
Join us on an exhilarating journey alongside the fearless fishermen of the hit reality TV show, Deadliest Catch. As the icy grip of winter tightens, these courageous crews face unimaginable challenges in their relentless pursuit of the prized Alaskan king crab. With every passing day, the crews find themselves locked in an epic struggle against Mother Nature's wrath. Winter storms relentlessly pound their vessels, testing their seamanship and fortitude. Battling icy waves and bone-chilling winds, these fishing heroes undergo heart-stopping moments that push them to their physical and mental limits. But the tempestuous seas aren't their only concern. Unpredictable weather conditions and dwindling supplies compound the crews' determination to succeed. As the unforgiving winter takes hold, the race against time intensifies, and the struggle for survival becomes all too real.

Sig Hansenâ€™s experience on "Deadliest Catch" shows how a public figure can smartly manage fame, keeping control over personal and professional life. This is very different from Josh Harris, who chased fame recklessly and ended up in legal trouble. Sig's story teaches us about the careful management of oneâ€™s public image, especially when moving from being a private person to a public figure.

Sverre Hansen and his father Sigurd, from KarmÃ¸y, Norway, moved to America in 1958 and started fishing for Opilio crabs, also known as snow crabs, in the unexplored waters of the Bering Sea. Their pioneering work let them fish all year round and opened up new opportunities for all fishermen, leading to profitable crab fishing seasons. This effort has brought significant income to both Sig and other fishermen during the harsh Opilio season. Over the years, "Deadliest Catch" has turned into a diverse show featuring different types of crab seasons: the regular king crab season, the less common Bairdi crab season, and the most dangerous, the Opilio crab season.

column1: Jake Anderson: "We've Caught $13 Million Dollars!" | Deadliest Catch
column5:
Million worth of crab during the gripping Season 18 finale of the Deadliest Catch. Amidst the icy dangers of the Bering Sea, Jake Anderson and fellow captains faced perilous waters, mechanical mishaps, and the relentless pursuit of the lucrative Alaskan king and snow crabs. Despite the harrowing risks and staggering challenges, these intrepid fishermen persisted, driven by the promise of life-changing rewards. As they battled against nature's fury and mechanical setbacks, each haul became a testament to their resilience and unwavering determination. From the heart-stopping race against time to repair crucial equipment to the exhilarating rush of hauling in millions of dollars' worth of crab, the journey of the FV Saga and its crew encapsulates the triumphs and tribulations of one of America's most dangerous professions

column1: What They Just Caught On Deadliest Catch SHOCKS Everybody!
column5:
What They Just Caught On Deadliest Catch SHOCKS Everybody!

The boat is heading 260 miles northeast of Dutch Harbor to finish off the King crab season. The captain, Jonathan Hillstrand, seems more upbeat than usual, as this is their fourth outing this season. Heâ€™s quite pleased with their catch so far, which includes numbers in the forties and fifties. The whole crew shares his excitement, even though some folks jokingly call them 'short-timers.' If Jonathan can navigate through this final challenge, they'll be on their way home. These guys, each about 45 years old, are seasoned enough to handle whatever the sea throws at them. Soon, theyâ€™re pulling up their crab pots filled with the crabs theyâ€™ve been chasing, and they even catch a rogue crab trying to escape.
 
All season long, theyâ€™ve been placing their pots in some well-kept spots in the ocean, and itâ€™s been paying off big time. Jonathan is particularly happy about one pot thatâ€™s overflowing with crabs, calling it a 'sweet spot.' Meanwhile, Steven is thrilled about finishing up soon because this big catch means they can head back earlier than planned. Suddenly, their gear gets caught up with another boat's equipment. Mike notices right away, and thereâ€™s no time to waste figuring out whose gear it is or where the other boat is. They just need to get untangled without damaging their own gear. They manage to avoid a major mess and breathe a sigh of relief because the last thing anyone wants is to dive into freezing water to cut away tangled lines. With only 13 pots left and a storm breathing down their necks, they need to fill up their storage fast.

column1: Frontiers of Election Reform: 5 Views on the Alaska Legislature (Part One)
column5:
â€œThe notion of getting rid of a closed primary system in Alaska appealed to me instantly,â€ says former Alaska House Speaker Bryce Edgmon who has represented Bristol Bay and parts of the Aleutian Islands for nearly two decades. â€œIt overrode right there almost on the spot any trepidation I might have about having to rank candidates or anything else that would eventually become part of the ballot measure that narrowly passed in Alaska.â€

Rep. Edgmon is referring to Alaskaâ€™s first-in-nation passage of a final or top four voting system with a unified open primary plus ranked choice general election. In this episode we examine the dynamics of the first state legislature in the country to have been elected by this system in 2022, even as a ballot measure to repeal the system has been put before Alaska voters in 2024.

We also discuss the dynamics of the Alaska legislature with Anchorage Daily News Reporter, Iris Samuels, and University of Alaska Southeast Political Science Professor, Dr. Glenn Wright. 

 â€œAlaska is fairly unique in that even before this election reform, we've had bipartisan and tri-partisan coalitions in the House and Senate,â€ says Samuels, who covers the Juneau State House. â€œBut it has reinforced that phenomenon and made it possible for elected officials to envision doing that and not experience repercussions from within their party and from voters.â€ 

â€œIf you talk to incumbent politicians,â€ explains Dr. Wright, â€œ they will tell you that they're less concerned about the primary challenge nowâ€“ that before the reform that was in the back of their mind. And they were thinking not about what do voters in my district want but what do party primary voters in my district want.â€

AFL-CIO President Joelle Hall has also observed what might be a similar deepening of Alaskaâ€™s cross-partisan tendencies in the two years since passage of the top four reform. 

â€œOne of the ways that we are really different is that we have always come to a bipartisan coalition at the end of every decade,â€ observes Hall, a legislative lobbyist for nearly three decades. â€œRedistricting happens. Then slowly the two parties claw back to roughly even. So it's accelerated what is already a normal path in Alaska where we gravitate towards these coalitions.

But our final guest on this first of two Alaska episodes, Rep. Alyse Galvin of Anchorage, cautions that these post reform dynamics have not yet translated into legislative action. Thatâ€™s partially because senior house leadership has blocked several bipartisan legislative efforts, while others were vetoed at the executive level. 

â€œif we don't allow this to play out a bit more, I'd say one more cycle, maybe two,â€ says Galvin, previously a two time candidate for the US House, â€then we're really missing a big chance to get things done that will give Alaskans hope.â€

Tune in for five different perspectives on the first legislature in the country elected by final or top four voting as citizens in four other US states (NV, ID, CO & MT) consider passing the Alaskan model for less divisive elections toward more collaborative governance.

column1: What Really Happened to Edgar Hansen From Deadliest Catch
column5:
What Really Happened to Edgar Hansen From Deadliest Catch

While Discovery Channel has produced some excellent reality TV, none of them compares to The Deadliest Catch. Since two thousand and five, the show has remained a fixture in Discovery's programming lineup, showing no signs of going away. Over the course of more than 18 seasons, Deadliest Catch highlights the host of Bering Sea Fishermen and their never-ending battle to obtain large crab hauls and earn even larger payouts, showcasing both heartwarming victories and heartbreaking defeats. This indicates that while the moniker "Deadliest Catch" may not sound intimidating, the job is challenging for those who dare to go on the show.

Keep watching as we reveal What Really Happened to Edgar Hansen From Deadliest Catch!

column1: Deadliest Catch: The Game | Xbox Series X Gameplay | First Look
column5:
Deadliest Catch: The Game Xbox Series X Gameplay First Look

Description
Hey, you! Yes, you! Do you want to be a landlubber your whole life? Or maybe you dream of making a fortune, sailing dangerous seas and learning the secrets of king crab catchers? Are you not afraid of risk, storms and crab claws? If you are brave enough, come with me to Dutch Harbor!

For a few days every year, experienced crab catchers and greenhorns brave the side of the element by side, putting their health and life on the line. The goal is to earn a fortune and become known as the best crab catcher. Now you can become one of them!

In Deadliest Catch: The Game you will compete in dangerous sea rallies to catch more crabs than you ever thought possible. The task is not simple â€“ it is a battle against time, fishing quotas, crab migrations, and most importantly: the sea. Such is your fate on the Alaskan waters!

Your ship is no different from those that sail from Dutch Harbor every fall to seek a fortune in the marine abyss. You will conn your vessel in all conditions: breeze or gale, no storm can scare you, however terrifying it may look. The troubled sea, the soaked ship deck, the vessel floating on the waves - and you to overcome it all!

At your disposal, we leave not only this fishing vessel, but also all the onboard equipment - the crane, the winch, the launcher, and the coiling system. We will teach you to use them, step by step. Remember, no-one was born with the rudder - or a crab - in their hand. However, you will manage the vessel by yourself - as captain and fisherman at the same time. All devices are handled by you in the first-person mode to have the best view of everything happening on your boat. You will also get original crab pots - thanks to them you will be able to pick out all the crabs from the vastness of Bering Sea.

Remember that you must follow Alaskan law. Not all crabs can be caught and sold! A realistic 3D model will help you judge whether you have caught a handsome and expensive male, a protected female, or a baby. Analyze the water and seabed to better predict where crabs may be found.

Nature will not be your only opponent. Match your skills against the computer and other players! Invite your friends to compete for the title of the best crab catcher. Load your pots on board, sit at the controls of your ship and see which one of you is the fastest and most effective in catching your crab fortune from the bottom of the sea!

Published by
Ultimate Games
Release date
6/28/2023

column1: Deadliest Catch Crab Fishermen's Tour
column5:
The Bering Sea Crab Fishermen's Tour is a 3-hour boat tour that departs from Ketchikan, Alaska.Â 

The tour takes you aboard the Aleutian Ballad, a crabbing vessel that was featured on season 2 of the Discovery Channel's "Deadliest Catch." During the tour, you will learn about the history of crab fishing in Alaska, see how crab pots are set and retrieved, and have the opportunity to help haul in the catch. You may also see some of the abundant wildlife in the area, such as bald eagles, sea lions, and whales.

The tour is family-friendly and suitable for all ages. It is a great way to experience the excitement of crab fishing and learn about the Alaskan way of life.

Here are some of the things you can expect on the Bering Sea Crab Fishermen's Tour:

Learn about the history of crab fishing in Alaska
See how crab pots are set and retrieved
Help haul in the catch
See abundant wildlife, such as bald eagles, sea lions, and whales
Enjoy stunning scenery of the Alaskan Inside Passage
Have a fun and educational experience for all ages

column1: How Rich Is Captain Sig Hansen from  Deadliest catch
column5:
Sig Hansen advanced through the Northwestern's ranks to take on the role of relief skipper.
He assumed full-time command of the ship at the age of 24.
The ship has had a stellar safety and gross production record while he has been in command.
Out of all the ships on Deadliest Catch, the North-western made the most money in 2005 and 2006!
But, thatâ€™s not all.
In the year 2020, the captain announced that his fishing operations were being negatively impacted by the coronavirus outbreak.
He said that he was spending "hundreds of thousands" of dollars on boat maintenance in order to get ready for the next months, even while he acknowledged that he was fortunate to be able to continue fishing and earn money.
In his role as the Hansen patriarch, Sig remains fiercely protective of his top-producing operation, his reputation, and his crew.
But then the past several seasons have tested the resolve of the stalwart Captain Sig.
From suffering a major heart attack to losing a close friend in the tragic sinking of the F/V Destination, Captain Sig has battered the blows of a career on the sea.

column1: Captain Sig Hansen's Greatest Moments | Deadliesnt Catch
column5:
Everyone is shocked by what they just caught on Dealiest Catch!

Being a crab fisherman for fun or for a living is a scary and risky job. Because people could get hurt, have a crash, or trip and fall. There is, however, a group of crabbing pros called Time Bandits whose job it is to show how to fish an expensive dish in the world. They are going on their last trip for the King crab season this year. What will they find? Are they ready to make a big catch? Let's go on a trip where we ride the big waves to catch the biggest crabs deep in the sea.

The Time Bandit is racing 260 miles northeast of Dutch Harbor to end the king crab season this time. Jonathan Hillstrand, the team leader, is very excited about their fourth trip of the season. He said, "We got forty and fifty, so I'm happy." I'm happy now, even though I think these numbers are great.

The team members are also happy, even though some people have called them "short-timers." On the other hand, a huge storm comes in from the west and could destroy them. They are going home if Jonathan's last plan works.

column1: Remembering the Covenant with David
Deadliest Catch : The Game | Ep2 Golden King Crabs
column5:
Enter the dangerous world of king crab fishing in the deadly Bering Sea! Take command of your own fishing vessel, use realistic equipment, combat hazardous Alaskan waters and become the world's best crab catcher!

Currently on STEAM for Â£16.75

DEVELOPER:   4Fishing
PUBLISHER:   Ultimate Games S.A.
A Discovery Channel Studio Game

WHAT THE DEVELOPERS HAVE TO SAY:

Hey, you! Yes, you! Do you want to be a landlubber your whole life? Or maybe you dream of making a fortune, sailing dangerous seas and learning the secrets of king crab catchers? Are you not afraid of risk, storms and crab claws? If you are brave enough, come with me to Dutch Harbor!

For a few days every year, experienced crab catchers and greenhorns brave the side of the element by side, putting their health and life on the line. The goal is to earn a fortune and become known as the best crab catcher. Now you can become one of them!

In Deadliest Catch: The Game you will compete in dangerous sea rallies to catch more crabs than you ever thought possible. The task is not simple â€“ it is a battle against time, fishing quotas, crab migrations, and most importantly: the sea. Such is your fate on the Alaskan waters!

Your ship is no different from those that sail from Dutch Harbor every fall to seek a fortune in the marine abyss. You will conn your vessel in all conditions: breeze or gale, no storm can scare you, however terrifying it may look. The troubled sea, the soaked ship deck, the vessel floating on the waves - and you to overcome it all!

At your disposal, we leave not only this fishing vessel, but also all the onboard equipment - the crane, the winch, the launcher, and the coiling system. We will teach you to use them, step by step. Remember, no-one was born with the rudder - or a crab - in their hand. However, you will manage the vessel by yourself - as captain and fisherman at the same time. All devices are handled by you in the first-person mode to have the best view of everything happening on your boat. You will also get original crab pots - thanks to them you will be able to pick out all the crabs from the vastness of Bering Sea.

Remember that you must follow Alaskan law. Not all crabs can be caught and sold! A realistic 3D model will help you judge whether you have caught a handsome and expensive male, a protected female, or a baby. Analyze the water and seabed to better predict where crabs may be found.

Nature will not be your only opponent. Match your skills against the computer and other players! Invite your friends to compete for the title of the best crab catcher. Load your pots on board, sit at the controls of your ship and see which one of you is the fastest and most effective in catching your crab fortune from the bottom of the sea!

column1: Cause of Death: 'Deadliest Catch' star passes away following a'medical emergency'
column5:
The reason of death for Nick Mavar, who is most renowned for his work on the reality show Deadliest Catch, is listed as a "medical emergency."
Nick is best known to viewers of the reality show as one of the deckhands on the well-liked Discovery program.
At the age of just fifty-nine.
Alaskan Nick Mavar passed away on Thursday, June 13.
The Bristol Bay Borough Police Department's Police Chief claims that he experienced a medical issue in the municipality of Naknek. The chief told Deadline that after being transferred to the hospital, he passed away from natural causes.
Though followers of the Deadliest Catch series will remember, he really departed the series in 2020 following a medical crisis. No further information was supplied. On board one of the ships, his appendix burst; the entire incident was captured on tape and broadcast during his last season.
However, there is no evidence that one circumstance is related to the other.
Fans of the show knew Nick as one of the deckhands with a slightly harsh exterior. He oversaw mechanical equipment maintenance and served as the lead on board Sig Hansen's F/V Northwestern.
Between 2005 and 2021, he starred in 98 episodes of Deadliest Catch and other spinoffs, such as Deadliest Catch: Siberian Winter and Deadliest Catch: The Bait. 
His tenure with the team was abruptly terminated when he filed a lawsuit against the F/V Northwestern's owners, claiming an inadequate strategy had been in place to provide him with appropriate medical care during the pandemic.
Nick sadly passed away a few days after Deadliest Catch Captain "Wild" Bill Wichrowski revealed in public that he had prostate cancer.

What Really Happened to Edgar Hansen From Deadliest Catch
column5:
What Really Happened to Edgar Hansen From Deadliest Catch

The Discovery Channel has produced several notable reality TV shows, but none quite compare to "Deadliest Catch." Since its debut in 2005, this show has remained a staple on Discoveryâ€™s lineup, enduring for over 18 seasons. "Deadliest Catch" chronicles the relentless efforts of Bering Sea fishermen as they strive to secure massive crab hauls and earn substantial paychecks, capturing both their triumphant victories and heart-wrenching losses.

The title "Deadliest Catch" isn't just for show; it reflects the challenging and perilous nature of the job for those who dare to appear on it. Among these brave individuals, a few have become fan favorites, making their adventures compelling viewing regardless of their luck. Notable cast members include siblings Jake and Josh, Captain Anderson, and Edgar Hansen, who gained prominence in season 9 and kept viewers hooked with their exploits.

Edgar Hansen, in particular, left a lasting impression since his debut. He took over the operations of the F/V Northwestern from his legendary brother Sig and worked closely with his niece Mandy to uphold their familyâ€™s legacy. After four active seasons, Edgar Hansen's sudden absence from the show left fans curious. Letâ€™s delve into what really happened to Edgar Hansen from "Deadliest Catch."
